 in WWII-era fiction by Gore Vidal and John Horne Burns, as well as from such wide-ranging sources as psychiatry texts, child development books, the memoirs of veterans’ children, and a slew of vernacular snapshots of happy male couples. In this sweeping reinterpretation of the postwar years, Ibson argues that a prolonged mourning for tenderness lost lay at the core of midcentury American masculinity, leaving far too many men with an unspoken ache that continued long after the fighting stopped, forever damaging their relationships with their wives, their children, and each other.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literature-20th century-History and criticism. 0aBurns, John Horne,-1916-1953-Appreciation-United States. 0aHomophobiazUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aHomophobia-United States-History-20th century. 0aHomosexuality and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aHomosexuality and literature-United States-History-20th century. 0aMale friendshipzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMale friendship-United States-History-20th century. 0aMasculinityzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMasculinity-United States-History-20th century. 0aMenzUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMen-United States-History-20th century. 0aUnited States-Social life and customs-1945-1970. 0aVidal, Gore,-1925-2012-Appreciation-United States. 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh  aGore Vidal.  aJohn Horne Burns.  aeveryday photography.  ahomophobia.  aintimacy.  amasculinity.  amen's relationships.  amidcentury America.  amourning.  apostwar America.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311068858040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780